SIMPLE: flower
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flower
<hw>Flow"er</hw> <pr>(flou"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>flour</ets>, OF. <ets>flour</ets>, <ets>flur</ets>,
<ets>flor</ets>, F. <ets>fleur</ets>, fr. L. <ets>flos</ets>,
<ets>floris</ets>. Cf. <er>Blossom</er>, <er>Effloresce</er>,
<er>Floret</er>, <er>Florid</er>, <er>Florin</er>, <er>Flour</er>,
<er>Flourish</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In the popular sense, the
bloom or blossom of a plant; the showy portion, usually of a different
color, shape, and texture from the foliage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>That part of a plant destined to
produce seed, and hence including one or both of the sexual organs; an
organ or combination of the organs of reproduction, whether inclosed by
a circle of foliar parts or not. A complete <xex>flower</xex> consists
of two essential parts, the stamens and the pistil, and two floral
envelopes, the corolla and callyx. In mosses the flowers consist of a
few special leaves surrounding or subtending organs called archegonia.
See <er>Blossom</er>, and <er>Corolla</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 574 --></p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ If we examine a common flower, such for instance as a
geranium, we shall find that it consists of: First, an outer envelope or
<xex>calyx</xex>, sometimes tubular, sometimes consisting of separate
leaves called <xex>sepals</xex>; secondly, an inner envelope or
<xex>corolla</xex>, which is generally more or less colored, and which,
like the calyx, is sometimes tubular, sometimes composed of separate
leaves called <xex>petals</xex>; thirdly, one or more
<xex>stamens</xex>, consisting of a stalk or <xex>filament</xex> and a
head or <xex>anther</xex>, in which the <xex>pollen</xex> is produced;
and fourthly, a <xex>pistil</xex>, which is situated in the center of
the flower, and consists generally of three principal parts; one or more
compartments at the base, each containing one or more seeds; the
<xex>stalk</xex> or <xex>style</xex>; and the <xex>stigma</xex>, which
in many familiar instances forms a small head, at the top of the style
or ovary, and to which the pollen must find its way in order to
fertilize the flower.</note> <rj><au>Sir J. Lubbock.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The fairest, freshest, and choicest part of
anything; <as>as, the <ex>flower</ex> of an army, or of a family</as>;
the state or time of freshness and bloom; <as>as, the <ex>flower</ex> of
life, that is, youth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The choice and <qex>flower</qex> of all things profitable the
Psalms do more briefly contain.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>flower</qex> of the chivalry of all Spain.</q>
<rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A simple maiden in her <qex>flower</qex>⟦br⟧
Is worth a hundred coats of arms.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Grain pulverized; meal; flour.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>flowers</qex> of grains, mixed with water, will make a
sort of glue.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld> <def>A substance
in the form of a powder, especially when condensed from sublimation;
<as>as, the <ex>flowers</ex> of sulphur</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A figure of speech; an ornament of style.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>Ornamental type
used chiefly for borders around pages, cards, etc.</def> <rj><au>W.
Savage.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Menstrual discharges.</def>
<rj><au>Lev. xv. 24.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Animal flower</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Animal</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Cut flowers</b></col>, <cd>flowers cut
from the stalk, as for making a bouquet.</cd> -- <col><b>Flower
bed</b></col>, <cd>a plat in a garden for the cultivation of
flowers.</cd> -- <col><b>Flower beetle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>any beetle which feeds upon flowers, esp. any one of numerous small
species of the genus <gen>Meligethes</gen>, family
<fam>Nitidulid⟦ae⟧</fam>, some of which are injurious to crops.</cd> --
<col><b>Flower bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an Australian bird
of the genus <gen>Anthornis</gen>, allied to the honey eaters.</cd> --
<col><b>Flower bud</b></col>, <cd>an unopened flower.</cd> --
<col><b>Flower clock</b></col>, <cd>an assemblage of flowers which open
and close at different hours of the day, thus indicating the time.</cd>
-- <col><b>Flower head</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a compound
flower in which all the florets are sessile on their receptacle, as in
the case of the daisy.</cd> -- <col><b>Flower pecker</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>one of a family (<fam>Dic⟦ae⟧id⟦ae⟧</fam>) of
small Indian and Australian birds. They resemble humming birds in
habits.</cd> -- <col><b>Flower piece</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A table
ornament made of cut flowers.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld>
<cd>A picture of flowers.</cd> -- <col><b>Flower stalk</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the peduncle of a plant, or the stem that
supports the flower or fructification.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flower</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flower
<hw>Flow"er</hw> <pr>(flou"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Flowered</conjf>
<pr>(flou"⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flowering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From the noun. Cf.
<er>Flourish</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To blossom; to bloom; to
expand the petals, as a plant; to produce flowers; <as>as, this plant
<ex>flowers</ex> in June</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To come into the finest or fairest
condition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their lusty and <qex>flowering</qex> age.</q> <rj><qau>Robynson
(More's Utopia).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When <qex>flowered</qex> my youthful spring.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To froth; to ferment gently, as new beer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That beer did <qex>flower</qex> a little.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To come off as flowers by sublimation.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Observations which have <qex>flowered</qex> off.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flower</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flower
<hw>Flow"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To embellish with flowers; to
adorn with imitated flowers; <as>as, <ex>flowered</ex>
silk</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flowerage</ent>⟦br⟧
